    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Feature already in Vim?\n\nno\n\n### Feature description\n\nThe new `vim.fs.find` is neat overall so thanks for adding that. I was trying to use it to launch some LSP servers depending if the root directory had `somepath/somefile` and `find(\"somefile\", { path = \"somepath\" }` worked great in the happy case where that eventually existed.\r\n\r\nHowever I just ran into a situation where the `somepath` directory is never there, and it raises an unhelpful exception, which was a bit hard to figure out that the real reason was of the directory not existing \r\n\r\n```\r\nnix run github:neovim/neovim\\?dir=contrib -- -u NONE --headless \\\r\n-c 'lua =vim.fs.find(\"afile\", { path=\"dir_exists_not\"})' -c 'q!'\r\n\r\nError detected while processing command line:\r\nE5108: Error executing lua ...eovim-unwrapped-master/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/fs.lua:181: bad argument #1 to '(for generator)' (uv_req expected, got nil)\r\nstack traceback:\r\n\t[C]: in function '(for generator)'\r\n\t...eovim-unwrapped-master/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/fs.lua:181: in function 'find'\r\n\t[string \":lua\"]:1: in main chunk‚èé\r\n```\r\n\r\nI think in this situation, find should return `{}` the same as if the file didn't exist. Does that make sense?",
